  • Interpretation:

    • Race
    • Education

  • Here the menopause age is linearly dependent to the intake_age, this is greatly reasonable, since at the intake age, no subject is having a menopause. The subject with higher intake age are not at risk at their own intake age, but the subject with lower intake age will be at risk at those age different period.

  • For example, if 1 person has intake age 49, then she will definitely have menopause_age > 49, but menopause_age \(\neq\) 49 , but for the subject intake with age 45, she will be at risk at age 49;

II. [TB] Starting at birth: Study on meno_age

[narr] In this study, only the women with no menopause at the recruitment time are chosen in the model, which means those who has menopause before the threshold is not selected, which will cause bias. This forms a left-truncated and right-censored(LTRC) data.

Here, the intake_age is regarded as the left-truncated time.

[Discussion] * In the problem, the quasi-independent is assumed. This independence implies the intake age should be irrelavant to the menopause age given the covariates when using the age onset as the outcome; * But here in our data, a clear linear relationship between intake age and menopause time;

PH model for additional contribution

\[ \begin{aligned} h_i(t) &= h_0(t)exp(\eta_i)\\ \eta_i&=\beta_1I(race=black)_i\\ &+\beta_2I(race=others)_i\\ &+\beta_3I(education=college graduate)_i\\ &+\beta_4I(education=some college)_i\\ &+\beta_5I(education=high school or less)_i \end{aligned} \]

  • For subject i, black and subject k, others, with the same education

\[ HR(t) = \frac{h_i(t)}{h_k(t)}=exp(\beta_1-\beta_2) \] * Interpretation:

Conditioning on the same education level and survival beyond t, the probability that subject i is menopause at time t is 2.64 times the probability that subject k is menopaused at time t

  • an estimate of the baseline survival function for White non-Hispanic patients with Post- graduate education

From the results, the assumption of PH holds well

Use the cox.zph function from the survival package. It results in two main things:

  1. A hypothesis test of whether the effect of each covariate differs according to time, and a global test of all covariates at once. This is done by testiung for an interaction effect between the covariate and log(time). A significant p-value indicates that the proportional hazards assumption is violated

  2. Plots of the Schoenfeld residuals Deviation from a zero-slope line is evidence that the proportional hazards assumption is violated
